The paper proposes a novel graph neural network framework for learning node representations that incorporate high-order feature interactions on feature-sparse graphs. This problem falls under the category of network representation learning, which is a fundamental research problem in machine learning. The paper also mentions the use of neural networks and graph-structured data, which are common topics in the sub-categories of cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the proposed framework involves the extraction of embeddings and the use of attentive fusion networks, which are techniques commonly used in the sub-categories of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.CL (Computation and Language). Finally, the paper presents experimental results on various datasets, which suggests that it could also belong to the sub-category of cs.CV (Computer Vision) if the datasets involve image-based graphs.
